The German pronunciation of the letter W is very short; in English, it's "double u".  That's too long for impatient Americans, so they substitute something that takes about .2 seconds less to say.

But in German, you probably wouldn't save any time at all.

@Times Rita 
Bobo the clown was actually a well-known central figure in some classic psychology studies performed in the early 60’s at Stanford University by Albert Bandura. An inflatable, cheerful looking, clown doll named Bobo was either subjected to violent behavior by an adult in front of nursery school aged children , or not subjected to such behavior. Subsequently, children exposed to the violent behavior were more likely to themselves exhibit violent behavior toward Bobo. This social leaning experiment was cited in Congressional hearings as evidence that that violent video games could encourage kids to act out violently. The original studies have been the subject of considerable controversy in ensuing years. See:

